							<table width="100%" border="0" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0">
								<tr>
									<td align="left" valign="middle" nowrap="nowrap" bgcolor="#faea38">
										<p class="course-header"><a id="phil1" name="phil1"></a>Philosophy 1</p>
									</td>
									<td align="center" valign="middle" nowrap="nowrap" bgcolor="#faea38" width="100%">
										<p class="course-header">Introduction to Philosophy</p>
									</td>
									<td align="right" valign="middle" nowrap="nowrap" bgcolor="#faea38">
										<p class="course-header">BUCHN 1910 | MWF 10:00-10:50 + Discussion</p>
									</td>
								</tr>
								<tr>
									<td colspan="3">
										<p class="course-body">Can free action exist in a purely deterministic world? Is the existence of evil compatible with the existence of a perfect being? These are some of the questions we will examine during the course of the quarter. The views of Plato and Descartes, two important philosophical figures, will receive attention. Hopefully, students will develop an appreciation for the subject matter of philosophy as well as the method of philosophical inquiry. Tentative course requirements include two papers (3-5 pages) and an in-class final.<br />
											<br />
											<b>Required Text(s):</b><br />
												Cottingham, Meditations on First Philosophy. Seech, Writing Philosophy Papers. Perry, A Dialogue on Personal Identity and Immortality. Reader</p>
									</td>
								</tr>
								<tr>
									<td colspan="3" align="left" valign="middle" bgcolor="#cccccc">
										<p class="course-footer"><b>Instructor:</b> <a href="../grad_profiles/buford.html">C. Buford</a></p>
									</td>
								</tr>
							</table>
							<hr class="course-desc" noshade="noshade" />
							<table width="100%" border="0" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0">
								<tr>
									<td align="left" valign="middle" nowrap="nowrap" bgcolor="#faea38">
										<p class="course-header"><a id="phil3" name="phil3"></a>Philosophy 3</p>
									</td>
									<td align="center" valign="middle" nowrap="nowrap" bgcolor="#faea38" width="100%">
										<p class="course-header">Critical Thinking</p>
									</td>
									<td align="right" valign="middle" nowrap="nowrap" bgcolor="#faea38">
										<p class="course-header">GIRV 1004 | MWF 9:00-9:50 + Discussion</p>
									</td>
								</tr>
								<tr>
									<td colspan="3">
										<p class="course-body">If you take this class, then you will learn to think critically. Therefore, if you do not take this class, then you will not learn to think critically. You do wish to learn to think critically. So, you should take this class. Convinced? You shouldn't be. The previous paragraph is an example of bad reasoning. Why? Take this class and find out. The primary topic of concern in this class will be arguments. Along the way, numerous concepts (e.g. validity, soundness, deduction/induction) will be introduced to further the analysis. Informal fallacies will be covered and students will be introduced to a formal system of propositional logic. Dealing with this formal system will occupy a fair amount of our time. Methods for assessing arguments containing categorical statements, statements relating two classes, will also be introduced. Anyone interested in correct reasoning is strongly encouraged to take this class. This class falls under the World Civilization and Thought GE requirement as well. As if that wasn't enough incentive, this class will also benefit those students planning on taking such standardized tests as the GRE or LSAT.<br />
											<br />
											<b>Required Text(s):</b><br />
												Hurley, A Concise Introduction to Logic (with Infotrec)</p>
									</td>
								</tr>
								<tr>
									<td colspan="3" align="left" valign="middle" bgcolor="#cccccc">
										<p class="course-footer"><b>Instructor:</b> D. Boyd</p>
									</td>
								</tr>
							</table>
							<hr class="course-desc" noshade="noshade" />
							<table width="100%" border="0" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0">
								<tr>
									<td align="left" valign="middle" nowrap="nowrap" bgcolor="#faea38">
										<p class="course-header"><a id="phil4" name="phil4"></a>Philosophy 4</p>
									</td>
									<td align="center" valign="middle" nowrap="nowrap" bgcolor="#faea38" width="100%">
										<p class="course-header">Introduction to Ethics</p>
									</td>
									<td align="right" valign="middle" nowrap="nowrap" bgcolor="#faea38">
										<p class="course-header">EMBAR HALL | MWF 11:00-11:50 + Discussion</p>
									</td>
								</tr>
								<tr>
									<td colspan="3">
										<p class="course-body">In this class, we will survey the modern ethical territory by examining issues in applied ethics, theoretical ethics, and the challenges of environmentalism, feminism, and multiculturalism to ethics. Here are some of the questions we will explore in the first part of the class: Is death bad? Are people who 'luck out' and receive little or no consequences for their 'immoral' actions less morally culpable? In what sense is sexual perversion wrong? Under what circumstances is war morally permissible? Are the moral standards of people who have political power different from those who do not? What is good about equality and is it permissible for people to prefer certain individuals over others based on race or gender? In the second part of the class, we will explore issues in ethical theory such as: In what sense are people who lack concern for others a challenge to ethics? Is ethics subjective or relative? What does 'good' mean? Are only people required to act ethically, and if so, why? In the third segment of the class, we will explore the biases upon which we have formulated many of our answers to ethical dilemmas. We will examine the challenges of environmentalism, feminism, and multiculturalism to ethical theory and seek a theory which is well-informed.<br />
											<br />
											<b>Required Text(s):</b><br />
												Nagel, Moral Questions<br />
												Williams, Morality: An Introduction to Ethics<br />
												Sterba, Three Challenges to Ethics</p>
									</td>
								</tr>
								<tr>
									<td colspan="3" align="left" valign="middle" bgcolor="#cccccc">
										<p class="course-footer"><b>Instructor:</b> <a href="../grad_profiles/salazar.html">H. Salazar</a></p>
									</td>
								</tr>
							</table>
							<hr class="course-desc" noshade="noshade" />
							<table width="100%" border="0" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0">
								<tr>
									<td align="left" valign="middle" nowrap="nowrap" bgcolor="#faea38">
										<p class="course-header"><a id="phil7" name="phil7"></a>Philosophy 7</p>
									</td>
									<td align="center" valign="middle" nowrap="nowrap" bgcolor="#faea38" width="100%">
										<p class="course-header">Biomedical Ethics</p>
									</td>
									<td align="right" valign="middle" nowrap="nowrap" bgcolor="#faea38">
										<p class="course-header">BUCHN 1940 | MWF 12:00-12:50 + Discussion</p>
									</td>
								</tr>
								<tr>
									<td colspan="3">
										<p class="course-body">This course will deal with moral controversies that arise in a biomedical ethics. The issues to be examined are human cloning, surrogate motherhood, abortion, physician-assisted suicide, euthanasia, human and animal research, organ procurement, lying to patients, decision making for the incompetent, etc. The student's grade for the course will be the result of a short paper (2-3 pages), a midterm exam, a longer paper (4-5 pages), and a cumulative final exam. The course will use a reader which will be available at GrafikArt in Isla Vista. For more information contact the instructor through the philosophy department in South Hall or by email at fritz88777@aol.com<br />
											<br />
											<b>Required Text(s):</b><br />
												Reader</p>
									</td>
								</tr>
								<tr>
									<td colspan="3" align="left" valign="middle" bgcolor="#cccccc">
										<p class="course-footer"><b>Instructor:</b> <a href="../graduate_students.html#allhoff">F. Allhoff</a></p>
									</td>
								</tr>
							</table>
							<hr class="course-desc" noshade="noshade" />
							<table width="100%" border="0" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0">
								<tr>
									<td align="left" valign="middle" nowrap="nowrap" bgcolor="#faea38">
										<p class="course-header"><a id="phil20b" name="phil20b"></a>Philosophy 20B</p>
									</td>
									<td align="center" valign="middle" nowrap="nowrap" bgcolor="#faea38" width="100%">
										<p class="course-header">History of Philosophy</p>
									</td>
									<td align="right" valign="middle" nowrap="nowrap" bgcolor="#faea38">
										<p class="course-header">IV THEA1 | MWF 2:00-2:50 + Discussion</p>
									</td>
								</tr>
								<tr>
									<td colspan="3">
										<p class="course-body">This class will be a survey course of selected philosophers from the Medieval and early Modern period. We will begin by looking at the battle between faith and rationality and proofs for the existence of god (central problems in Medieval philosophy within the branches of philosophy of religion and ontology). We will look at the writings of Augustine, Boethius, Anslem, and Aquinas. In the middle part of this course we will look at the medieval debate on universals between the realists and the nominalists. Leaving behind the medieval period, and moving on to the early modern period we will look at the political philosophy of Hobbes in light of formal techniques in game theory. The course will close with a critical in depth examination of Descartes' Meditations on First Philosophy, perhaps the greatest early modern philosophical treatise. Time permitting we may look at the work of either (or all) Spinoza, Leibniz, Malbranche or Pascal. There will be a midterm examination, 2 short papers 750-900 words each, and a non-cumulative final exam. There will be an honors section for those honors students that are interested. The honors section will consist of critical discussions of the material drawing from secondary sources from contemporary literature. Please contact anand@umail.ucsb.edu for any questions or inquiries.<br />
											<br />
											<b>Required Text(s):</b><br />
												Cottingham, Meditations on First Philosophy. Reader</p>
									</td>
								</tr>
								<tr>
									<td colspan="3" align="left" valign="middle" bgcolor="#cccccc">
										<p class="course-footer"><b>Instructor:</b> <a href="../graduate_students.html#vaidya">A. Vaidya</a></p>
									</td>
								</tr>
							</table>
							<hr class="course-desc" noshade="noshade" />
							<table width="100%" border="0" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0">
								<tr>
									<td align="left" valign="middle" nowrap="nowrap" bgcolor="#faea38">
										<p class="course-header"><a id="phil100b" name="phil100b"></a>Philosophy 100B</p>
									</td>
									<td align="center" valign="middle" nowrap="nowrap" bgcolor="#faea38" width="100%">
										<p class="course-header">Theory of Knowledge</p>
									</td>
									<td align="right" valign="middle" nowrap="nowrap" bgcolor="#faea38">
										<p class="course-header">BRDA 1640 | TR 9:30-10:45 + Discussion</p>
									</td>
								</tr>
								<tr>
									<td colspan="3">
										<p class="course-body">The main character of The Matrix discovers that, despite initial appearances, he does not live in 20th century America. Instead, he is a slave living inside &quot;the Matrix,&quot; a futuristic computer program which has systematically fooled him into believing that he lives in 20th century America. Of course, most of us believe that we live in 20th century America, not inside the Matrix. But why should we be so sure? Wouldn't the world seem exactly the same to me even if I were living inside the Matrix? If so, then how can I know either way? Can I ever be certain that the world is in fact as it appears to be? Philosophers have been debating these questions for centuries. We will explore some prominent contributions to the ongoing philosophical debate. We will then discuss more general issues concerning the nature of knowledge, justification, and rationality.<br />
											<br />
											<b>Required Text(s):</b><br />
												Feldman, Epistemology. Rosenberg, Three Conversations about Knowing. Reader</p>
									</td>
								</tr>
								<tr>
									<td colspan="3" align="left" valign="middle" bgcolor="#cccccc">
										<p class="course-footer"><b>Instructor:</b> <a href="../fac_profiles/rescorla.html">M. Rescorla</a></p>
									</td>
								</tr>
							</table>
							<hr class="course-desc" noshade="noshade" />
							<table width="100%" border="0" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0">
								<tr>
									<td align="left" valign="middle" nowrap="nowrap" bgcolor="#faea38">
										<p class="course-header"><a id="phil100e" name="phil100e"></a>Philosophy 100E</p>
									</td>
									<td align="center" valign="middle" nowrap="nowrap" bgcolor="#faea38" width="100%">
										<p class="course-header">Metaphysics</p>
									</td>
									<td align="right" valign="middle" nowrap="nowrap" bgcolor="#faea38">
										<p class="course-header">SH 1431 | MWF 11:00-11:50 + Discussion</p>
									</td>
								</tr>
								<tr>
									<td colspan="3">
										<p class="course-body">This course is an introduction to several fundamental topics in contemporary analytic metaphysics, including universals and particulars, necessity and possibility, the nature of time, and personal identity.<br />
											<br />
											<b>Required Text(s):</b><br />
												Loux, Metaphysics: Contemporary Readings</p>
									</td>
								</tr>
								<tr>
									<td colspan="3" align="left" valign="middle" bgcolor="#cccccc">
										<p class="course-footer"><b>Instructor:</b> <a href="../fac_profiles/falvey.html">K. Falvey</a></p>
									</td>
								</tr>
							</table>
							<hr class="course-desc" noshade="noshade" />
							<table width="100%" border="0" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0">
								<tr>
									<td align="left" valign="middle" nowrap="nowrap" bgcolor="#faea38">
										<p class="course-header"><a id="phil102a" name="phil102a"></a>Philosophy 102A</p>
									</td>
									<td align="center" valign="middle" nowrap="nowrap" bgcolor="#faea38" width="100%">
										<p class="course-header">Applied Analytical Reasoning</p>
									</td>
									<td align="right" valign="middle" nowrap="nowrap" bgcolor="#faea38">
										<p class="course-header">SNDCR 1649 | TR 9:30-10:45</p>
									</td>
								</tr>
								<tr>
									<td colspan="3">
										<p class="course-body">Intended as a sequel to Philosophy 3 (Critical Thinking), this course will be devoted partly to developing more sophisticated tools of formal logic and partly to furthering students' skills at informal argument analysis.<br />
											<br />
											<b>Required Text(s):</b><br />
												Reader</p>
									</td>
								</tr>
								<tr>
									<td colspan="3" align="left" valign="middle" bgcolor="#cccccc">
										<p class="course-footer"><b>Instructor:</b> <a href="../faculty.html#forgie">J.W. Forgie</a></p>
									</td>
								</tr>
							</table>
							<hr class="course-desc" noshade="noshade" />
							<table width="100%" border="0" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0">
								<tr>
									<td align="left" valign="middle" nowrap="nowrap" bgcolor="#faea38">
										<p class="course-header"><a id="phil112" name="phil112"></a>Philosophy 112/212G</p>
									</td>
									<td align="center" valign="middle" nowrap="nowrap" bgcolor="#faea38" width="100%">
										<p class="course-header">Philosophy of Religion</p>
									</td>
									<td align="right" valign="middle" nowrap="nowrap" bgcolor="#faea38">
										<p class="course-header">WEBB 1100 | TR 12:30-1:45</p>
									</td>
								</tr>
								<tr>
									<td colspan="3">
										<p class="course-body">An introductory survey of a number of philosophical issues connected with the concepts and beliefs making up the great monotheistic religious traditions of Judaism, Christianity and Islam. A large portion of the course deals with the concept of God and belief in the existence of God. We will examine what have been historically the most important arguments for the existence of God—the cosmological argument, the argument from design, and the ontological argument—as well as consider the evidential value for religious belief provided by the alleged occurrence of miracles, by the variety of religious or mystical experiences and by the alleged objectivity of morality. Then we will consider grounds and arguments against the existence of God, beginning with alleged incoherencies in the very concept of God and ending with an extensive consideration of what many consider the biggest obstacle to religious belief—the problem of evil and suffering. Finally, we will stand back from our deliberations and ask: in the light of all the arguments pro and con, is belief in God rational? At each stage we will come to grips with some of the best our ancestors have contributed to these issues—works by Plato, Aquinas, Anselm, Descartes, Hume, Kant, Pascal, Freud, James and Russell—as well as important writings of contemporary philosophers. Requirements are: final exam, plus two short papers.<br />
											<br />
											<b>Required Text(s):</b><br />
												Hume, Dialogues Concerning Natural Religion. Pojman, Philosophy of Religion</p>
									</td>
								</tr>
								<tr>
									<td colspan="3" align="left" valign="middle" bgcolor="#cccccc">
										<p class="course-footer"><b>Instructor:</b> <a href="../faculty.html#forgie">J.W. Forgie</a></p>
									</td>
								</tr>
							</table>
							<hr class="course-desc" noshade="noshade" />
							<table width="100%" border="0" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0">
								<tr>
									<td align="left" valign="middle" nowrap="nowrap" bgcolor="#faea38">
										<p class="course-header"><a id="phil116" name="phil116"></a>Philosophy 116/216G</p>
									</td>
									<td align="center" valign="middle" nowrap="nowrap" bgcolor="#faea38" width="100%">
										<p class="course-header">Meaning and Reference</p>
									</td>
									<td align="right" valign="middle" nowrap="nowrap" bgcolor="#faea38">
										<p class="course-header">SH 5705 | TR 2:00-3:15</p>
									</td>
								</tr>
								<tr>
									<td colspan="3">
										<p class="course-body">An examination of the classical theories of meaning and reference: John Stuart Mill, Gottlob Frege, Bertrand Russell, Saul Kripke, and the theory of direct reference. Issues to be discussed center on the following: what is the nature of the information content of a declarative sentence, and what do the constituents of the sentence contribute? How is the referent of a term secured? How is the information content of a sentence secured, and how is the contribution of the sentence constituents secured? Solutions to the classical puzzles of meaning and reference are investigated.<br />
											<br />
											<b>Required Text(s):</b><br />
												Garfield, Meaning and Truth. Salmon, Frege's Puzzle. Optional Text: Martinich, Philosophy of Language. Kripke, Naming and Necessity. Seech, Writing Philosophy Papers</p>
									</td>
								</tr>
								<tr>
									<td colspan="3" align="left" valign="middle" bgcolor="#cccccc">
										<p class="course-footer"><b>Instructor:</b> <a href="../fac_profiles/salmon.html">N. Salmon</a></p>
									</td>
								</tr>
							</table>
							<hr class="course-desc" noshade="noshade" />
							<table width="100%" border="0" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0">
								<tr>
									<td align="left" valign="middle" nowrap="nowrap" bgcolor="#faea38">
										<p class="course-header"><a id="phil122" name="phil122"></a>Philosophy 122/222G</p>
									</td>
									<td align="center" valign="middle" nowrap="nowrap" bgcolor="#faea38" width="100%">
										<p class="course-header">Theories of Justice</p>
									</td>
									<td align="right" valign="middle" nowrap="nowrap" bgcolor="#faea38">
										<p class="course-header">PHELP 1445 | R 3:30-6:20</p>
									</td>
								</tr>
								<tr>
									<td colspan="3">
										<p class="course-body">Problems of political liberalism, probably religion and culture.<br />
											<br />
											<b>Required Text(s):</b><br />
												Rawls, Political Liberalism. Reader</p>
									</td>
								</tr>
								<tr>
									<td colspan="3" align="left" valign="middle" bgcolor="#cccccc">
										<p class="course-footer"><b>Instructor:</b> <a href="../fac_profiles/wilkins.html">B. Wilkins</a></p>
									</td>
								</tr>
							</table>
							<hr class="course-desc" noshade="noshade" />
							<table width="100%" border="0" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0">
								<tr>
									<td align="left" valign="middle" nowrap="nowrap" bgcolor="#faea38">
										<p class="course-header"><a id="phil124" name="phil124"></a>Philosophy 124/224G</p>
									</td>
									<td align="center" valign="middle" nowrap="nowrap" bgcolor="#faea38" width="100%">
										<p class="course-header">Philosophy of Science</p>
									</td>
									<td align="right" valign="middle" nowrap="nowrap" bgcolor="#faea38">
										<p class="course-header">GIRV 2127 | TR 12:30-1:45</p>
									</td>
								</tr>
								<tr>
									<td colspan="3">
										<p class="course-body">Logical positivism was a philosophical movement that flourished in Vienna during the 1930s. The positivists sought to purge philosophy of what they viewed as its pernicious metaphysical tendencies. They generally dismissed religion and ethics as nonsense. They applauded natural science as a paradigm of knowledge, and they constructed systematic philosophical theories designed to accommodate the latest scientific developments. Collectively, the positivists produced some of the best and most important philosophy of the twentieth century. Even though few people still accept positivism's central doctrines, one cannot even begin to understand contemporary philosophy without examining those doctrines. We will study the major elements of positivism, focusing upon Rudolf Carnap's mature work. We will conclude by discussing W. V. Quine's influential critique of positivism. Note: although the only official prerequisite for this course is one previous philosophy class, prior enrollment in Phil 100F is recommended for undergraduates.<br />
											<br />
											<b>Required Text(s):</b><br />
												Reader</p>
									</td>
								</tr>
								<tr>
									<td colspan="3" align="left" valign="middle" bgcolor="#cccccc">
										<p class="course-footer"><b>Instructor:</b> <a href="../fac_profiles/rescorla.html">M. Rescorla</a></p>
									</td>
								</tr>
							</table>
							<hr class="course-desc" noshade="noshade" />
							<table width="100%" border="0" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0">
								<tr>
									<td align="left" valign="middle" nowrap="nowrap" bgcolor="#faea38">
										<p class="course-header"><a id="phil129" name="phil129"></a>Philosophy 129/229G</p>
									</td>
									<td align="center" valign="middle" nowrap="nowrap" bgcolor="#faea38" width="100%">
										<p class="course-header">Philosophy of International Relations</p>
									</td>
									<td align="right" valign="middle" nowrap="nowrap" bgcolor="#faea38">
										<p class="course-header">PHELP 1445 | W 3:30-6:20</p>
									</td>
								</tr>
								<tr>
									<td colspan="3">
										<p class="course-body">Problems in international relations, probably we'll start with Kant's &quot;Perpetual Peace&quot;.<br />
											<br />
											<b>Required Text(s):</b><br />
												Rawls, The Law of Peoples. Reader</p>
									</td>
								</tr>
								<tr>
									<td colspan="3" align="left" valign="middle" bgcolor="#cccccc">
										<p class="course-footer"><b>Instructor:</b> <a href="../fac_profiles/wilkins.html">B. Wilkins</a></p>
									</td>
								</tr>
							</table>
							<hr class="course-desc" noshade="noshade" />
							<table width="100%" border="0" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0">
								<tr>
									<td align="left" valign="middle" nowrap="nowrap" bgcolor="#faea38">
										<p class="course-header"><a id="phil131" name="phil131"></a>Philosophy 131/231G</p>
									</td>
									<td align="center" valign="middle" nowrap="nowrap" bgcolor="#faea38" width="100%">
										<p class="course-header">Advanced Topics in Applied Ethics</p>
									</td>
									<td align="right" valign="middle" nowrap="nowrap" bgcolor="#faea38">
										<p class="course-header">BSIF 1217 | MWF 2:00-2:50</p>
									</td>
								</tr>
								<tr>
									<td colspan="3">
										<p class="course-body">This course will examine the grounds for punishment. What, if anything, justifies the exacting of punishments? Is it intrinsically good that the guilty be punished? Is it intrinsically bad when anyone gets punished? What are the appropriate aims of punishment? What, if anything, can morally excuse a guilty party from being punished? We'll also discuss the connection between responsibility and punishment, and punishment's role in moral education or training.<br />
											<br />
											<b>Required Text(s):</b><br />
												Simmons, Cohen and Beitz, Punishment: A Philosophy and Public Affairs Reader. Murphy, Punishment and Rehabilitation. Baird and Rosenbaum, Punishment and the Death Penalty: The Current Debate</p>
									</td>
								</tr>
								<tr>
									<td colspan="3" align="left" valign="middle" bgcolor="#cccccc">
										<p class="course-footer"><b>Instructor:</b> <a href="../fac_profiles/zimmerman.html">A. Zimmerman</a></p>
									</td>
								</tr>
							</table>
							<hr class="course-desc" noshade="noshade" />
							<table width="100%" border="0" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0">
								<tr>
									<td align="left" valign="middle" nowrap="nowrap" bgcolor="#faea38">
										<p class="course-header"><a id="phil135" name="phil135"></a>Philosophy 135/235G</p>
									</td>
									<td align="center" valign="middle" nowrap="nowrap" bgcolor="#faea38" width="100%">
										<p class="course-header">Contemporary Philosophy</p>
									</td>
									<td align="right" valign="middle" nowrap="nowrap" bgcolor="#faea38">
										<p class="course-header">GIRV 2124 | TR 11:00-12:15</p>
									</td>
								</tr>
								<tr>
									<td colspan="3">
										<p class="course-body">The course will examine the philosophy of pragmatism and some arguments that have been made against it. An underlying theme will be how the normative dimension of human life should be understood.<br />
											<br />
											<b>Required Text(s):</b><br />
												Rorty, Contingency, Irony and Solidarity. Kripke, Wittgenstein on Rules and Private Language. Nagel, The Last Word</p>
									</td>
								</tr>
								<tr>
									<td colspan="3" align="left" valign="middle" bgcolor="#cccccc">
										<p class="course-footer"><b>Instructor:</b> <a href="../fac_profiles/mcmahon.html">C. McMahon</a></p>
									</td>
								</tr>
							</table>
							<hr class="course-desc" noshade="noshade" />
							<table width="100%" border="0" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0">
								<tr>
									<td align="left" valign="middle" nowrap="nowrap" bgcolor="#faea38">
										<p class="course-header"><a id="phil149" name="phil149"></a>Philosophy 149/249G</p>
									</td>
									<td align="center" valign="middle" nowrap="nowrap" bgcolor="#faea38" width="100%">
										<p class="course-header">Action Theory</p>
									</td>
									<td align="right" valign="middle" nowrap="nowrap" bgcolor="#faea38">
										<p class="course-header">ARTS 1247 | TR 2:00-3:15</p>
									</td>
								</tr>
								<tr>
									<td colspan="3">
										<p class="course-body">The course will investigate a number of topics in contemporary action theory, such as the distinction between action and behavior, the individuation of actions, the phenomena of intention and the problem of free will.<br />
											<br />
											<b>Required Text(s):</b><br />
												Frankfurt, The Importance of What We Care About</p>
									</td>
								</tr>
								<tr>
									<td colspan="3" align="left" valign="middle" bgcolor="#cccccc">
										<p class="course-footer"><b>Instructor:</b> <a href="../fac_profiles/mcmahon.html">C. McMahon</a></p>
									</td>
								</tr>
							</table>
							<hr class="course-desc" noshade="noshade" />
							<table width="100%" border="0" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0">
								<tr>
									<td align="left" valign="middle" nowrap="nowrap" bgcolor="#faea38">
										<p class="course-header"><a id="phil151" name="phil151"></a>Philosophy 151/251G</p>
									</td>
									<td align="center" valign="middle" nowrap="nowrap" bgcolor="#faea38" width="100%">
										<p class="course-header">Pre-Socratics</p>
									</td>
									<td align="right" valign="middle" nowrap="nowrap" bgcolor="#faea38">
										<p class="course-header">HSSB 1206 | MW 3:00-4:15</p>
									</td>
								</tr>
								<tr>
									<td colspan="3">
										<p class="course-body">Greek philosophy had been flourishing for over a century when Socrates was born (469 b.c.). Socrates' thought, as well as that of all later Greek philosophers, was strongly influenced by the work of the early pioneers in the field, both the philosopher-scientists known as 'Presocratics' and the fifth-century Sophists. The aim of this course is to examine the theories, arguments and concepts of these thinkers and to show why they are important historically as well as in their own right.<br />
											<br />
											<b>Required Text(s):</b><br />
												McKirahan, Philosophy Before Socrates. Hussey, The Presocratics. Kirk, Raven and Schofield, The Presocratic Philosophers</p>
									</td>
								</tr>
								<tr>
									<td colspan="3" align="left" valign="middle" bgcolor="#cccccc">
										<p class="course-footer"><b>Instructor:</b> <a href="../fac_profiles/tsouna.html">V. Tsouna</a></p>
									</td>
								</tr>
							</table>
							<hr class="course-desc" noshade="noshade" />
							<table width="100%" border="0" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0">
								<tr>
									<td align="left" valign="middle" nowrap="nowrap" bgcolor="#faea38">
										<p class="course-header"><a id="phil163" name="phil163"></a>Philosophy 163/263G</p>
									</td>
									<td align="center" valign="middle" nowrap="nowrap" bgcolor="#faea38" width="100%">
										<p class="course-header">Locke</p>
									</td>
									<td align="right" valign="middle" nowrap="nowrap" bgcolor="#faea38">
										<p class="course-header">PHELP 1508 | MWF 12:00-12:50</p>
									</td>
								</tr>
								<tr>
									<td colspan="3">
										<p class="course-body">John Locke's Essay Concerning Human Understanding was the most important book written in English on epistemology and metaphysics in the seventeenth century. In it, Locke sought to show that we perceive the world by means of ideas, which are the signs of objects, and communicate with each other by means of words, which are the signs of ideas. This course will examine Locke's Essay in detail, looking first at his theory of ideas, their origin, their kinds, and how they represent things to the mind; then at his theory of language and how words function as signs of ideas to make communication possible; and finally at his division of human cognition into knowledge and belief, looking carefully at his account of what things it is possible for us to have knowledge of, and what things we can form reliable beliefs about, including his views about the extent and limits of our knowledge of the human mind itself, of the physical universe, and of God. There will be a midterm, a final, and two six-page papers.<br />
											<br />
											<b>Required Text(s):</b><br />
												Locke, Essay Concerning Human Understanding</p>
									</td>
								</tr>
								<tr>
									<td colspan="3" align="left" valign="middle" bgcolor="#cccccc">
										<p class="course-footer"><b>Instructor:</b> <a href="../faculty.html#mccracken">C. McCracken</a></p>
									</td>
								</tr>
							</table>
							<hr class="course-desc" noshade="noshade" />
							<table width="100%" border="0" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0">
								<tr>
									<td align="left" valign="middle" nowrap="nowrap" bgcolor="#faea38">
										<p class="course-header"><a id="phil166a" name="phil166a"></a>Philosophy 166A/266A</p>
									</td>
									<td align="center" valign="middle" nowrap="nowrap" bgcolor="#faea38" width="100%">
										<p class="course-header">Kant</p>
									</td>
									<td align="right" valign="middle" nowrap="nowrap" bgcolor="#faea38">
										<p class="course-header">BLD 387 RM 101 | MW 9:30-10:45</p>
									</td>
								</tr>
								<tr>
									<td colspan="3">
										<p class="course-body">Prerequisites: two prior courses from Philosophy 20B, 100B-D-E, or 160. A close examination of the main metaphysical and epistemological doctrines of Kant's Critique of Pure Reason.<br />
											<br />
											<b>Required Text(s):</b><br />
												Kant, Critique of Pure Reason</p>
									</td>
								</tr>
								<tr>
									<td colspan="3" align="left" valign="middle" bgcolor="#cccccc">
										<p class="course-footer"><b>Instructor:</b> <a href="../faculty.html#schwyzer">H. Schwyzer</a></p>
									</td>
								</tr>
							</table>
							<hr class="course-desc" noshade="noshade" />
							<table width="100%" border="0" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0">
								<tr>
									<td align="left" valign="middle" nowrap="nowrap" bgcolor="#faea38">
										<p class="course-header"><a id="phil184" name="phil184"></a>Philosophy 184/284G</p>
									</td>
									<td align="center" valign="middle" nowrap="nowrap" bgcolor="#faea38" width="100%">
										<p class="course-header">Intermediate Modern/Advanced Symbolic Logic</p>
									</td>
									<td align="right" valign="middle" nowrap="nowrap" bgcolor="#faea38">
										<p class="course-header">SH 5617 | TR 11:00-12:15</p>
									</td>
								</tr>
								<tr>
									<td colspan="3">
										<p class="course-body">Application and development of first order predicate logic with identity and descriptions. An introduction to metalogical results: Lowenheim-Skolem, Compactness, Completeness.<br />
											<br />
											<b>Required Text(s):</b><br />
												Hunter, Metalogic. Kalish, Logic: Techniques of Formal Reasoning. Hughes, Philosophical Companions to First Order Logic</p>
									</td>
								</tr>
								<tr>
									<td colspan="3" align="left" valign="middle" bgcolor="#cccccc">
										<p class="course-footer"><b>Instructor:</b> <a href="../fac_profiles/salmon.html">N. Salmon</a></p>
									</td>
								</tr>
							</table>
							<hr class="course-desc" noshade="noshade" />
							<table width="100%" border="0" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0">
								<tr>
									<td align="left" valign="middle" nowrap="nowrap" bgcolor="#faea38">
										<p class="course-header"><a id="phil296b" name="phil296b"></a>Philosophy 296B</p>
									</td>
									<td align="center" valign="middle" nowrap="nowrap" bgcolor="#faea38" width="100%">
										<p class="course-header">Seminar in Epistemology</p>
									</td>
									<td align="right" valign="middle" nowrap="nowrap" bgcolor="#faea38">
										<p class="course-header">SH 5617 | R 3:30-6:20</p>
									</td>
								</tr>
								<tr>
									<td colspan="3">
										<p class="course-body">We will read current articles on skepticism about knowledge of the external world. We will start with contextualist answers to skepticism.<br />
											<br />
											<b>Required Text(s):</b><br />
												Reader</p>
									</td>
								</tr>
								<tr>
									<td colspan="3" align="left" valign="middle" bgcolor="#cccccc">
										<p class="course-footer"><b>Instructor:</b> <a href="../fac_profiles/brueckner.html">A. Brueckner</a></p>
									</td>
								</tr>
							</table>
							<hr class="course-desc" noshade="noshade" />
							<table width="100%" border="0" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0">
								<tr>
									<td align="left" valign="middle" nowrap="nowrap" bgcolor="#faea38">
										<p class="course-header"><a id="phil298a" name="phil298a"></a>Philosophy 298A</p>
									</td>
									<td align="center" valign="middle" nowrap="nowrap" bgcolor="#faea38" width="100%">
										<p class="course-header">Seminar in Aesthetics</p>
									</td>
									<td align="right" valign="middle" nowrap="nowrap" bgcolor="#faea38">
										<p class="course-header">SH 5617 | W 3:30-6:20</p>
									</td>
								</tr>
								<tr>
									<td colspan="3">
										<p class="course-body">Originality seems to be a universally admired aesthetic property, except when it results in original nonsense. In this seminar we will examine some traditional philosophical conceptions of artistic genius (Plato, Longinus, Kant) and test these conceptions against what is known or believed about artists who have come be considered geniuses. We will also consider the analogies and contrasts between them and alleged scientific geniuses. The aim is to gain clarity on the concept of genius itself and assess its historic vacillations in aesthetics.<br />
											<br />
											<b>Required Text(s):</b><br />
												Kivy, The Possessor and the Possessed: Handel, Mozart, Beethoven and the Idea of Musical Genius</p>
									</td>
								</tr>
								<tr>
									<td colspan="3" align="left" valign="middle" bgcolor="#cccccc">
										<p class="course-footer"><b>Instructor:</b> <a href="../faculty.html#crawford">D. Crawford</a></p>
									</td>
								</tr>
							</table>
							<hr class="course-desc" noshade="noshade" />
							<table width="100%" border="0" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0">
								<tr>
									<td align="left" valign="middle" nowrap="nowrap" bgcolor="#faea38">
										<p class="course-header"><a id="phil299a" name="phil299a"></a>Philosophy 299A</p>
									</td>
									<td align="center" valign="middle" nowrap="nowrap" bgcolor="#faea38" width="100%">
										<p class="course-header">Seminar in the Philosophy of Logic</p>
									</td>
									<td align="right" valign="middle" nowrap="nowrap" bgcolor="#faea38">
										<p class="course-header">SH 5705 | T 3:30-6:20</p>
									</td>
								</tr>
								<tr>
									<td colspan="3">
										<p class="course-body">Our topic in this seminar will be the question of the philosophical significance of second-order logic. After a brief introduction to the rudiments of second-order logic and its standard semantics, we will go on to consider such questions as whether first-order predicate logic should be considered to contain the whole of logic, properly so-called. This view is most prominent in the works of W. V. O. Quine, but has been attributed to other important logicians and philosophers (e.g. Skolem and Godel) and seems to have a large following at present in the general philosophical and logical community. This inquiry will lead us to consider the limitations and positive attributes of first-order logic, the question of what it is for something to be a logical constant, and various questions about the ontological and mathematical commitments of second-order logic. We will also consider the possibility and significance of intensional interpretations of second-order logic as a logic of properties. Each student will be required to regularly attend the seminar, to make a critical presentation of one of the readings, and to write a term paper of not more than 20 pages on a topic connected with the subject of the seminar. We will read works by Quine, Stewart Shapiro, Leslie Tharp, George Boolos, Alfred Tarksi, Nino Cocchiarella, and others.<br />
											<br />
											<b>Required Text(s):</b><br />
												Reader, Grafikart Copy Service, 6550 Pardall Road, Isla Vista.</p>
									</td>
								</tr>
								<tr>
									<td colspan="3" align="left" valign="middle" bgcolor="#cccccc">
										<p class="course-footer"><b>Instructor:</b> <a href="../fac_profiles/anderson.html">C. A. Anderson</a></p>
									</td>
								</tr>
							</table>
							<h3>Sabbatical and Leave Information</h3>
							<p class="bodytext">Professor Hanser will be on sabbatical Winter 2004.</p>
